english:
  title: Letter Presented to Minister Mun Sang-si Sik
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I humbly submit this letter to you, Esteemed Scholar of the Palace.

    There was a matter of import that compelled me to seek your counsel. When I called upon your residence, you received me with such warmth and grace, and not only welcomed me kindly but set forth wine that we might drink freely and pass the hours in joy together.

    During our leisured conversation, you turned your gaze upon me repeatedly and spoke these words: "A scholar must take humility and caution as his guiding principles. In recent times there was a poet named Lin Chun who, trusting in his talents, looked down upon others. Yet despite his gifts, he never advanced even once through the examinations, and died in poverty and hunger. Your abilities are no lesser than his, and you maintain constant humility with never a trace of arrogance. Your appearance too is robust and lustrous—surely you are destined for great things." Your single word of encouragement carries the weight of a thousand pieces of gold. How could I, being neither wood nor stone, fail to be moved to tears?

    Yet upon reflection, though I may appear indolent and presumptuous, I find it difficult to display such failings before my betters. For I have long marveled at those who grasp their brush and grow proud, saying: "Those who command wealth and power shine with brilliance and stand in dignity. Their authority is enough to command multitudes, their power enough to hold sway over life and death. Thus people fear them, serve them, and have no leisure even to await their commands—who would dare question their righteousness?" Though such arrogance might persist unpunished, yet in the end none escape their own stumbling.

    And those possessed of unusual strength of body—their fists may intimidate and control others, and though they strut and posture, none will gainsay them. Yet history shows that those who rely on strength alone never endure long.

    But what of letters and learning? They are but modest talents. Though one may store within them wonders embroidered with silk and gold, these are reverenced and feared only by one's true friends, not by all people. Should one grow proud of such gifts and treat others with contempt, one will surely meet with violence and humiliation—and worse, fall into unforeseen calamity.

    Therefore did Ni Heng, proud before others, meet his end at the hands of Huang Zu. And Ji Kang, relying on his spirit, suffered injustice from Zhong Hui. Such fates befell countless ancients whose stories are woven through history, bright as mirrors for our reflection.

    Thus, those who study the rise and fall of the ancients understand that humility and caution flow naturally from such wisdom, even for those possessed of great talent. As for one like myself, surveying my own being, I find nothing whatsoever that might warrant pride or carelessness. Though I bow my head to the earth, I dare not raise it. Shrunken and timid, I carry always a sense of great shame—which is only the natural course of things.

    Yet that you should address me thus—is it not to urge me toward ever greater self-discipline and the preservation of my being? Though I am slow of wit, how could I fail to cherish your words?

    The *Book of History* teaches: "Humility brings increase; pride brings loss." The *Analects* say: "Reverence approaches propriety and keeps shame at bay." These have been familiar to my ears and lodged in my heart since my first studies. With your wise instruction now reinforcing this wisdom, I shall inscribe it upon my very seat and make it my mirror morning and night, ever correcting my heart.

    Whether I rise to great heights or not rests with Heaven and Fate. Yet should I have a patron such as yourself, who lends me wings and the strength of wind, how could the path before me be blocked? I remain your humble servant.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ni Heng (禰衡) and Huang Zu (黃祖): Historical figures from the Eastern Han period. Ni Heng, known for his talent and pride, was killed by the warlord Huang Zu.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ji Kang (嵇康) and Zhong Hui (鍾會): Philosophers from the Western Jin dynasty. Ji Kang, celebrated for his character and learning, was executed through the machinations of Zhong Hui.'
  - key: ''
    value: The quoted passages are from the *Book of History* (書經) and the *Analects* (論語), foundational Confucian texts that emphasize the virtue of humility.
